The Data

The data set for this assignment consists of college admissions data. It comes from an open data set available via https://www.kaggle.com/mohansacharya/graduate-admissions .

The dataset contains several parameters which are considered important during the application for Masters Programs. The parameters included are:

  1. GRE Scores ( out of 340 )
  2. TOEFL Scores ( out of 120 )
  3. University Rating ( out of 5 )
  4. Statement of Purpose and Letter of Recommendation Strength ( out of 5 )
  5. Undergraduate GPA ( out of 10 )
  6. Research Experience ( either 0 or 1 )
  7. Chance of Admit ( ranging from 0 to 1 )

The full citation for the data is:

Mohan S Acharya, Asfia Armaan, Aneeta S Antony : A Comparison of Regression Models for Prediction of Graduate Admissions, IEEE International Conference on Computational Intelligence in Data Science 2019.

Question 1 (5 points)

Explain what the previous R code block does.

Q1 Response:

The previous R code block (above) selects columns from our dataset and displays only those columns, with their names modified as a way to make coding with them easier. For example, GRE Score is renamed to gre. The mutate function has a factor function within it, making the research column our categorical variable. You can see that R knows this based on the glimpse(data) function below, where research is labeled as fct.

Question 2 (10 points)

Describe the shape of the distribution of the chance of admission. If you decide to use a histogram choose your width of your bins carefully.

ggplot(admissions_data, aes(x = admit)) +
  xlab("Chance of admission") +
  ylab("Count") +
  labs(title = "Amount of varying chances of admission") +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = .02, col = "white")

Q2 Response:

The chance of admission histogram follows a mostly normal distribution. There is a clear center where a majority of the counts lie, and the counts outside of the middle ~60% fall off in a somewhat predictable pattern.

Q5 Response:

Students with research experience 1) tend to have higher cumulative GPAs and 2) tend to have a higher chance of admission.

Question 6 (15 points)

Create a regression model that uses chance of admission as the outcome variable and Cumulative GPA and research experience as the explanatory variables. What is the expected (estimated) value of the chance of admission for an individual with a cumulative GPA of 9.0 who has research experience?

admissions_model_interaction <- lm(admit ~ cgpa * research, admissions_data)

am_int_reg <- get_regression_table(admissions_model_interaction)

Q6 Response:

In the code block above, my first method at arriving at the estimated value of a students chance of admission who possesses research experience, based on a cumulative GPA of 9.0, was to plug in the estimate numbers to the interaction model equation from our textbook. To check that score, I was lucky enough to find a regression point that matched the questions criteria exactly. I compared that regression point to my manually entered data, and they matched up closely. I furthermore ran the codier version of the interactive multiple regression equation and arrived at the same answer as my first method, y = 0.814 percent.

Q8 Response:

Both letters of recommendation and statements of purpose have relatively low r squared values as they correspond to chance of admission. r squared for sop = 45.7%, r sqaured for lor = 44.9%. Eachs correlation to chance of admission is relatively low as well. Based on their similarity, neither are more important for improving chance of admission. Or, you could say, each is the same importance. In any case, both pull less weight for chance of admission than other factors such as cumulative GPA or GRE score.
